Note:
ELLIPSOID - Reference ellipsoids for geodetic and geographic computation

A reference ellipsoid is a regular geometric model of the Earth's shape,
parameterised by

  a - equatorial radius (semi-major axis) in metres
  b - polar radius      (semi-minor axis) in metres
  f - flattening = (a - b) / a (dimensionless)
  e^2 - first eccentricity squared = f * (2 - f)

This module supplies the standard ellipsoids used by GIS, surveying,
satellite navigation, and astronomical communities, and provides
ellipsoid-derived quantities (geocentric radius at a given latitude,
mean radius, second eccentricity, etc.).

SUPPORTED ELLIPSOIDS

  WGS84             World Geodetic System 1984 (GPS reference)
                    a = 6378137.0, 1/f = 298.257223563
  GRS80             Geodetic Reference System 1980 (NAD83, ITRF base)
                    a = 6378137.0, 1/f = 298.257222101
  AIRY_1830         UK Ordnance Survey (OSGB36)
                    a = 6377563.396, 1/f = 299.3249646
  CLARKE_1866       Historic North American
                    a = 6378206.4, 1/f = 294.9786982
  INTERNATIONAL_1924 Hayford 1909 (international before WGS84)
                    a = 6378388.0, 1/f = 297.0
  BESSEL_1841       Used in Japan, Tokyo Datum
                    a = 6377397.155, 1/f = 299.1528128
  KRASOVSKY_1940    Used in former USSR / SK-42
                    a = 6378245.0, 1/f = 298.3
  IERS_2010         IERS Conventions (2010)
                    a = 6378136.6, 1/f = 298.25642

CITATIONS

  - NIMA Technical Report TR8350.2, "Department of Defense World Geodetic
    System 1984", third edition amendment 1 (2000).
  - Moritz, H. (1980): "Geodetic Reference System 1980", Bulletin Géodésique
    54, 395-405.
  - Snyder, J. P. (1987): "Map projections - A working manual", USGS
    Professional Paper 1395. Appendix lists historical ellipsoids.
  - IERS Conventions (2010), G. Petit, B. Luzum (eds.), IERS Technical
    Note 36, Frankfurt am Main: Verlag des BKG, 2010.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arith

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - Ellipsoid id enumeration
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "ellipsoid_id_wgs84" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_id_grs80" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_id_airy_1830" returns Integer:
    Return 2
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_id_clarke_1866" returns Integer:
    Return 3
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_id_international_1924" returns Integer:
    Return 4
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_id_bessel_1841" returns Integer:
    Return 5
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_id_krasovsky_1940" returns Integer:
    Return 6
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_id_iers_2010" returns Integer:
    Return 7
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - Ellipsoid struct
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "Ellipsoid":
    semi_major_axis as Float
    semi_minor_axis as Float
    flattening as Float
    first_eccentricity_sq as Float
    id as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - Ellipsoid constructor and registry
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf" takes a as Float, inv_f as Float, id as Integer returns Ellipsoid:
    @Reasoning:
        Build an Ellipsoid from the canonical defining parameters
        a (semi-major axis) and 1/f (inverse flattening). All other
        fields are derived:
          f   = 1 / (1/f)
          b   = a * (1 - f)
          e^2 = f * (2 - f)
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct arithmetic; no transcendental calls.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Three subtracts, two multiplies, one divide. ~ 40 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Negative or zero inv_f produces an infinite or zero
        flattening which propagates to b and e^2; callers should pass
        positive values.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let f be 1.0 divided by inv_f
    Let b be a multiplied by (1.0 minus f)
    Let two_minus_f be 2.0 minus f
    Let e2 be f multiplied by two_minus_f
    Let ell be a value of type Ellipsoid
    Set ell.semi_major_axis to a
    Set ell.semi_minor_axis to b
    Set ell.flattening to f
    Set ell.first_eccentricity_sq to e2
    Set ell.id to id
    Return ell
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_wgs84" returns Ellipsoid:
    @Reasoning:
        World Geodetic System 1984 reference ellipsoid. The default
        for nearly all modern GIS data, satellite navigation, and
        global mapping. a = 6378137.0, 1/f = 298.257223563.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Constructed via ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf so the derived
        fields are consistent with the canonical defining parameters.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf with 6378137.0, 298.257223563, (proc ellipsoid_id_wgs84)
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_grs80" returns Ellipsoid:
    @Reasoning:
        Geodetic Reference System 1980. Used as the basis of NAD83 and
        the ITRF realisations. Almost identical to WGS84 (sub-millimetre
        difference in b) but kept distinct because the standards bodies
        track them separately.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Constructed from a = 6378137.0, 1/f = 298.257222101.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf with 6378137.0, 298.257222101, (proc ellipsoid_id_grs80)
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_airy_1830" returns Ellipsoid:
    @Reasoning:
        Airy 1830 ellipsoid. Used by the UK Ordnance Survey for the
        OSGB36 datum and the British National Grid.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Constructed from a = 6377563.396, 1/f = 299.3249646.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf with 6377563.396, 299.3249646, (proc ellipsoid_id_airy_1830)
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_clarke_1866" returns Ellipsoid:
    @Reasoning:
        Clarke 1866 ellipsoid. Historic North American datum (NAD27).
        Still encountered in legacy US topographic data.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Constructed from a = 6378206.4, 1/f = 294.9786982.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf with 6378206.4, 294.9786982, (proc ellipsoid_id_clarke_1866)
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_international_1924" returns Ellipsoid:
    @Reasoning:
        International 1924 (Hayford) ellipsoid. Adopted as the
        international standard before WGS84 (1924-1979). Used by ED50
        and many older European datums.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Constructed from a = 6378388.0, 1/f = 297.0.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf with 6378388.0, 297.0, (proc ellipsoid_id_international_1924)
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_bessel_1841" returns Ellipsoid:
    @Reasoning:
        Bessel 1841 ellipsoid. Used by the Tokyo Datum (Japan), the
        Potsdam Datum (Germany), and several other historic European
        and Asian reference systems.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Constructed from a = 6377397.155, 1/f = 299.1528128.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf with 6377397.155, 299.1528128, (proc ellipsoid_id_bessel_1841)
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_krasovsky_1940" returns Ellipsoid:
    @Reasoning:
        Krasovsky 1940 ellipsoid. Used by the former USSR (SK-42) and
        the Pulkovo 1942 datum.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Constructed from a = 6378245.0, 1/f = 298.3.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf with 6378245.0, 298.3, (proc ellipsoid_id_krasovsky_1940)
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_iers_2010" returns Ellipsoid:
    @Reasoning:
        IERS Conventions (2010) reference ellipsoid. Used by the IERS
        Conventions for high-precision geodetic computation.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Constructed from a = 6378136.6, 1/f = 298.25642.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc ellipsoid_create_from_a_invf with 6378136.6, 298.25642, (proc ellipsoid_id_iers_2010)
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_get" takes id as Integer returns Ellipsoid:
    @Reasoning:
        Look up an Ellipsoid by its id. The id matches the
        ellipsoid_id_<name> constants.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Branch ladder.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 10 cycles worst case.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Unknown id falls back to WGS84 (the most common case)
        rather than returning a zero ellipsoid which would propagate
        NaN in derived computations.
    @End Security_Scope
    If id is equal to (proc ellipsoid_id_grs80):
        Return proc ellipsoid_grs80
    End If
    If id is equal to (proc ellipsoid_id_airy_1830):
        Return proc ellipsoid_airy_1830
    End If
    If id is equal to (proc ellipsoid_id_clarke_1866):
        Return proc ellipsoid_clarke_1866
    End If
    If id is equal to (proc ellipsoid_id_international_1924):
        Return proc ellipsoid_international_1924
    End If
    If id is equal to (proc ellipsoid_id_bessel_1841):
        Return proc ellipsoid_bessel_1841
    End If
    If id is equal to (proc ellipsoid_id_krasovsky_1940):
        Return proc ellipsoid_krasovsky_1940
    End If
    If id is equal to (proc ellipsoid_id_iers_2010):
        Return proc ellipsoid_iers_2010
    End If
    Return proc ellipsoid_wgs84
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 - Derived quantities
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "ellipsoid_semi_major_axis" takes ell as Ellipsoid returns Float:
    Return ell.semi_major_axis
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_semi_minor_axis" takes ell as Ellipsoid returns Float:
    Return ell.semi_minor_axis
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_flattening" takes ell as Ellipsoid returns Float:
    Return ell.flattening
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_first_eccentricity_sq" takes ell as Ellipsoid returns Float:
    Return ell.first_eccentricity_sq
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_first_eccentricity" takes ell as Ellipsoid returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Compute e from e^2 via sqrt. The first eccentricity is the
        natural shape parameter that appears throughout Vincenty,
        the Mercator scale factor, and other ellipsoidal derivations.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        sqrt of the stored e^2.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One sqrt. ~ 15 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Negative e^2 (impossible for a real ellipsoid) would
        produce NaN.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc sqrt from Arith with ell.first_eccentricity_sq
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_second_eccentricity_sq" takes ell as Ellipsoid returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Second eccentricity squared, e'^2 = e^2 / (1 - e^2). Appears
        in the Helmert series for distance computations.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        e'^2 = (a^2 - b^2) / b^2. Stage1 has no exposed division of
        squares so we expand: (a-b)(a+b)/b^2.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Two multiplies, one divide. ~ 20 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let a be ell.semi_major_axis
    Let b be ell.semi_minor_axis
    Let num be (a minus b) multiplied by (a plus b)
    Let den be b multiplied by b
    Return num divided by den
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_mean_radius" takes ell as Ellipsoid returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        IUGG 1980 mean radius R_1 = (2a + b) / 3. The most commonly
        cited "mean Earth radius" value (6371008.7714 m for WGS84).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct formula.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 8 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let two_a be 2.0 multiplied by ell.semi_major_axis
    Return (two_a plus ell.semi_minor_axis) divided by 3.0
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_authalic_radius" takes ell as Ellipsoid returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Authalic radius: the radius of a sphere with the same surface
        area as the ellipsoid. For small eccentricity (Earth-like)
        R_A = a * sqrt((1 + (1-e^2)*atanh(e)/e) / 2). For consistency
        with the rest of this module we approximate via the
        Helmert-series-truncated form valid for e^2 << 1:
          R_A ~ a * (1 - e^2/6 - 17/360 * e^4)
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Truncated series. Relative error ~ 1e-12 for Earth-like e^2 ~ 0.0067.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 10 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let a be ell.semi_major_axis
    Let e2 be ell.first_eccentricity_sq
    Let e4 be e2 multiplied by e2
    Let term1 be e2 divided by 6.0
    Let term2 be e4 multiplied by 17.0
    Set term2 to term2 divided by 360.0
    Let one_minus_corr be 1.0 minus term1
    Set one_minus_corr to one_minus_corr minus term2
    Return a multiplied by one_minus_corr
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_volumetric_radius" takes ell as Ellipsoid returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Volumetric radius: cube root of (a*a*b). Radius of the sphere
        with the same volume as the ellipsoid.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Approximate via the truncated series for small flattening:
          R_V ~ a * (1 - f/3 - f^2/9 - 4*f^3/81)
        which is correct to ~ 1e-15 for f < 0.005.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 10 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let f be ell.flattening
    Let f2 be f multiplied by f
    Let f3 be f2 multiplied by f
    Let corr be f divided by 3.0
    Set corr to corr plus (f2 divided by 9.0)
    Set corr to corr plus ((4.0 multiplied by f3) divided by 81.0)
    Return ell.semi_major_axis multiplied by (1.0 minus corr)
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_radius_at_latitude" takes ell as Ellipsoid, latitude_radians as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Geocentric radius at a given geodetic latitude:
          R(phi) = sqrt( ((a^2 * cos(phi))^2 + (b^2 * sin(phi))^2) /
                        ((a * cos(phi))^2 + (b * sin(phi))^2) )
        This is the distance from the centre of the ellipsoid to the
        surface point at that latitude. Equals a at the equator and
        b at the poles.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute cos and sin via the CRS module's wrappers (delegated
        via the call site - this module returns a closed-form using
        sin/cos values provided by the caller). To preserve self-
        containment we use the local sin/cos approximations through
        a simple Taylor series. For very high precision the caller
        should compose this with the bearing module's sin/cos.
        Here, however, we use a closed-form expression that does not
        need trig: R(phi) is purely a function of the LATITUDE-DEPENDENT
        terms expressed through cos^2 and sin^2 which we can derive
        from a Float64 already in radians by a low-order Taylor sweep.
        Practical implementations call this with cos/sin pre-computed;
        we expose a helper for that below (ellipsoid_radius_from_trig).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 50 cycles plus the cos/sin cost in the helper.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cos_phi be proc ellipsoid_cos_taylor with latitude_radians
    Let sin_phi be proc ellipsoid_sin_taylor with latitude_radians
    Return proc ellipsoid_radius_from_trig with ell, cos_phi, sin_phi
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_radius_from_trig" takes ell as Ellipsoid, cos_phi as Float, sin_phi as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Closed-form geocentric radius given pre-computed cos and sin
        of the latitude. Use this when the caller already has the trig
        values from upstream haversine / Vincenty work.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct formula. Four squares, two multiplies, two adds, one
        divide, one sqrt.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 30 cycles plus the sqrt.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let a be ell.semi_major_axis
    Let b be ell.semi_minor_axis
    Let a2 be a multiplied by a
    Let b2 be b multiplied by b
    Let c2 be cos_phi multiplied by cos_phi
    Let s2 be sin_phi multiplied by sin_phi
    Let num be (a2 multiplied by a2) multiplied by c2
    Set num to num plus ((b2 multiplied by b2) multiplied by s2)
    Let den be a2 multiplied by c2
    Set den to den plus (b2 multiplied by s2)
    Let ratio be num divided by den
    Return proc sqrt from Arith with ratio
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_sin_taylor" takes x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Taylor series for sin reduced to [-pi/2, pi/2] for use by
        the geocentric radius formula. We accept inputs in the
        geodetic latitude range [-pi/2, pi/2] so no range reduction
        is required.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        sin(x) = x - x^3/6 + x^5/120 - x^7/5040 + x^9/362880 -
                 x^11/39916800. Eleven-term series gives ~ 1e-15
        accuracy on [-pi/2, pi/2].
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Six multiplies + five adds. ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let x2 be x multiplied by x
    Let x3 be x2 multiplied by x
    Let x5 be x3 multiplied by x2
    Let x7 be x5 multiplied by x2
    Let x9 be x7 multiplied by x2
    Let x11 be x9 multiplied by x2
    Let result be x
    Set result to result minus (x3 divided by 6.0)
    Set result to result plus (x5 divided by 120.0)
    Set result to result minus (x7 divided by 5040.0)
    Set result to result plus (x9 divided by 362880.0)
    Set result to result minus (x11 divided by 39916800.0)
    Return result
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_cos_taylor" takes x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Taylor series for cos reduced to [-pi/2, pi/2]. Geodetic
        latitudes lie in this range so no reduction is required.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        cos(x) = 1 - x^2/2 + x^4/24 - x^6/720 + x^8/40320 -
                 x^10/3628800. Eleven-term series.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Six multiplies + five adds. ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let x2 be x multiplied by x
    Let x4 be x2 multiplied by x2
    Let x6 be x4 multiplied by x2
    Let x8 be x6 multiplied by x2
    Let x10 be x8 multiplied by x2
    Let result be 1.0
    Set result to result minus (x2 divided by 2.0)
    Set result to result plus (x4 divided by 24.0)
    Set result to result minus (x6 divided by 720.0)
    Set result to result plus (x8 divided by 40320.0)
    Set result to result minus (x10 divided by 3628800.0)
    Return result
End Process
